* Two Vogues, 25 years apart: I was excited to get my hands on the December=
 2024 issue of Vogue, edited by Marc Jacobs. I buy print magazines all the =
time, but I only subscribe to a handful (New York, The New Yorker, Garden &=
 Gun, and a few indie fashion titles). Serendipitously, the Marc issue show=
ed up outside my sliding doors just days before my husband hauled a pile of=
 old American Vogues home from his mother=E2=80=99s house in Chicago. (When=
 my husband and I started dating, he told me he knew nothing about fashion.=
 A few months later, I met my future mother-in-law, a collector of 1980s So=
nia Rykiel. Her magazine archive is, um, extensive. You can=E2=80=99t escap=
e your fate.)

I was able to juxtapose two issues, published almost exactly 25 years apart=
 (November 1999 and December 2024). Trudging through November 1999 was a fu=
n reminder of an era when a monthly magazine could still feel newsy. Vogue =
never
did those calendar pages=E2=80=94which always felt instantly outdated, anyw=
ay=E2=80=94but I enjoyed (current W magazine executive editor) Armand Limna=
nder=E2=80=99s 1999 dispatch on resort shoes and bags, edited by Michelle K=
essler. The society pages were a physical version of Instagram Stories, fea=
turing party shots of Mandy Moore wearing Daryl K and Phoebe Philo in Chlo=
=C3=A9 and a fake tan.

Those old issues were about fashion, not luxury. Back then, most people, ev=
en the wealthy, did not buy designer handbags or clothing, a reality reflec=
ted in the magazine=E2=80=99s advertising and content. Yes, there were Tiff=
any, Louis Vuitton, and Coach ads, but also cheesy classifieds and creative=
 for Winston cigarettes and Jockey bras. This complexion would change in th=
e coming years after Tom Florio took over as publisher from Richard =E2=80=
=9CMad Dog=E2=80=9D Beckman and LVMH and Kering began rapidly consolidating=
 and
concentrating their media-buying power.

In the December 2024 issue, aside from a stray page featuring a jumble of a=
s-seen-on-TV-type products=E2=80=94including a =E2=80=9Ctop device for thin=
ning hair=E2=80=9D and a canned Cosmopolitan infused with hemp-derived THC=
=E2=80=94the only advertisements left are luxury or fragrance. (Dooney & Bo=
urke and Olay were the only mass-market sponsors I counted.) Obviously, Goo=
gle and Meta offer more efficient and targeted marketing for C.P.G. brands=
=E2=80=94or any business trying to reach a consumer audience, honestly.

So yes, today=E2=80=99s magazine is diminished in all the expected ways: fe=
wer pages (186 in =E2=80=9925 versus a 544-page doorstop in =E2=80=9999), f=
ewer editors (although Hamish Bowles and Tonne Goodman appear on both masth=
eads under Anna Wintour), and far fewer advertisements. But all that turmoi=
l and downsizing has forced the remaining ideas people at Vogue to think re=
al hard about how to
make it a pleasure to read.

The best part of this Marc Jacobs-edited issue isn=E2=80=99t the unforgetta=
ble Steven Meisel shot of Kaia Gerber, or the designer=E2=80=99s delicious =
=E2=80=9Cmarket=E2=80=9D pages (featuring a purple Birkin, Prada pajamas, p=
ink Charvet slippers, Russ & Daughters caviar, and the most gorgeous Ariel =
Dearie spray of flowers). It isn=E2=80=99t the Alastair McKimm-styled, Inez=
 & Vinoodh-shot image of dancer Dakota Moore-Lizotte wearing that pink Ala=
=C3=AFa spiral of fluff in front of the Guggenheim. Or the oral history of =
celebrities going to the Met Gala on Marc=E2=80=99s arm. No, the best part =
was how in-the-moment it felt.

I had already read Edith Zimmerman=E2=80=99s essay about replacing alcohol =
with running, but it was a delight to see her weird little illustrations in=
 print. I was chuffed that the awesome William Eggleston exhibit at David Z=
wirner in Los Angeles,
