x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;"><ul style=3D"margin=
:0;color:#000000;font-size:16px;line-height:30px;margin-top:0;margin-bottom=
:0;list-style-type:square;mso-special-format:bullet"><li><i>It wasn=E2=80=
=99t an easy year for Hearst, either</i>: Unlike Cond=C3=A9 Nast, which she=
ds employees on a fairly regular basis to help hit revenue goals, Hearst=E2=
=80=99s magazine publishing arm is already run so conservatively that layof=
fs are typically a very last resort. I don=E2=80=99t remember the last time=
 I wrote about a round over there. Maybe two summers ago? (Yes, July 2023.)=
 Anyway, this morning, everyone was informed that a company-wide restructur=
ing is underway, with both editorial and commercial teams affected. No word=
 yet on how many layoffs there will be in total, or how long they=E2=80=99l=
l take to carry out, but this is definitely bigger than the 2023 round, and=
 probably one of the bigger rounds in recent
Hearst history. It will include, I=E2=80=99m told, consolidation in editori=
al operations roles, like managing editors and copy editors. <br/><br/>The =
macro challenges are real: Luxury advertisers have pared back their budgets=
 even further this year, digital media subscriptions are stagnating (especi=
ally at legacy publishers like Hearst, where they=E2=80=99re not breaking n=
ews <i>and</i> they=E2=80=99re not allowed to show any personality), and th=
e costs of doing business are rising. Hearst already instituted some layoff=
s this summer, including =E2=80=9Cdozens=E2=80=9D of people from the stream=
ing service Very Local. The cuts are difficult, a sign of the times, and no=
t great for morale. In a Zoom on Thursday afternoon, Hearst Magazines presi=
dent <b>Debi Chirichella</b> told staffers that the name of the game was <i=
>focus</i>: What the company is focusing on is working, and they just need =
to hone further. Want <i>me </i>to go further on this? You gotta reply to t=
his email or call me. +1 646-241-3902.  =20
<br/><br/></li><li><i>Two Vogues, 25 years apart</i>: I was excited to get =
my hands on the December 2024 issue of <i>Vogue</i>, edited by <b>Marc Jaco=
bs</b>. I buy print magazines all the time, but I only subscribe to a handf=
ul (<i>New York</i>, <i>The New Yorker, Garden &amp; Gun, </i>and a few ind=
ie fashion titles). Serendipitously, the Marc issue showed up outside my sl=
iding doors just days before my husband hauled a pile of old American <i>Vo=
gues</i> home from his mother=E2=80=99s house in Chicago. (When my husband =
and I started dating, he told me he knew nothing about fashion. A few month=
s later, I met my future mother-in-law, a collector of 1980s <b>Sonia Rykie=
l</b>. Her magazine archive is, um, extensive. You can=E2=80=99t escape you=
r fate.)<br/><br/>I was able to juxtapose two issues, published almost exac=
tly 25 years apart (November 1999 and December 2024). Trudging through Nove=
mber 1999 was a fun reminder of an era when a monthly magazine could still =
feel newsy. <i>Vogue </i>never
did those calendar pages=E2=80=94which always felt instantly outdated, anyw=
ay=E2=80=94but I enjoyed (current <i>W</i> magazine executive editor) <b>Ar=
mand Limnander</b>=E2=80=99s 1999 dispatch on resort shoes and bags, edited=
 by <b>Michelle Kessler</b>. The society pages were a physical version of I=
nstagram Stories, featuring party shots of <b>Mandy</b> <b>Moore</b> wearin=
g Daryl K and <b>Phoebe</b> <b>Philo</b> in Chlo=C3=A9 and a fake tan. <br/=
><br/>Those old issues were about <i>fashion</i>, not luxury. Back then, mo=
st people, even the wealthy, did not buy designer handbags or clothing, a r=
eality reflected in the magazine=E2=80=99s advertising and content. Yes, th=
ere were Tiffany, Louis Vuitton, and Coach ads, but also cheesy classifieds=
 and creative for Winston cigarettes and Jockey bras. This complexion would=
 change in the coming years after <b>Tom</b> <b>Florio</b> took over as pub=
lisher from <b>Richard</b> <b>=E2=80=9CMad Dog=E2=80=9D Beckman</b> and LVM=
H and Kering began rapidly consolidating and
concentrating their media-buying power. <br/><br/>In the December 2024 issu=
e, aside from a stray page featuring a jumble of as-seen-on-TV-type product=
s=E2=80=94including a =E2=80=9Ctop device for thinning hair=E2=80=9D and a =
canned Cosmopolitan infused with hemp-derived THC=E2=80=94the only advertis=
ements left are luxury or fragrance. (Dooney &amp; Bourke and Olay were the=
 only mass-market sponsors I counted.) Obviously, Google and Meta offer mor=
e efficient and targeted marketing for C.P.G. brands=E2=80=94or <i>any</i> =
business trying to reach a consumer audience, honestly.<br/><br/>So yes, to=
day=E2=80=99s magazine is diminished in all the expected ways: fewer pages =
(186 in =E2=80=9925 versus a <i>544</i>-page doorstop in =E2=80=9999), fewe=
r editors (although <b>Hamish</b> <b>Bowles</b> and <b>Tonne</b> <b>Goodman=
</b> appear on both mastheads under <b>Anna Wintour</b>), and far fewer adv=
ertisements. But all that turmoil and downsizing has forced the remaining i=
deas people at <i>Vogue</i> to think <i>real </i>hard about how to
make it a pleasure to read. <br/><br/>The best part of this Marc Jacobs-edi=
ted issue isn=E2=80=99t the unforgettable <b>Steven</b> <b>Meisel</b> shot =
of <b>Kaia</b> <b>Gerber</b>, or the designer=E2=80=99s delicious =E2=80=9C=
market=E2=80=9D pages (featuring a purple Birkin, Prada pajamas, pink Charv=
et slippers, Russ &amp; Daughters caviar, and the most gorgeous Ariel Deari=
e spray of flowers). It isn=E2=80=99t the <b>Alastair</b> <b>McKimm</b>-sty=
led, <b>Inez</b> &amp; <b>Vinoodh</b>-shot image of dancer <b>Dakota</b> <b=
>Moore-Lizotte</b> wearing that pink Ala=C3=AFa spiral of fluff in front of=
 the Guggenheim. Or the oral history of celebrities going to the Met Gala o=
n Marc=E2=80=99s arm. No, the best part was how <i>in-the-moment</i> it fel=
t. <br/><br/>I had already read <b>Edith</b> <b>Zimmerman</b>=E2=80=99s ess=
ay about replacing alcohol with running, but it was a delight to see her we=
ird little illustrations in print. I was chuffed that the awesome <b>Willia=
m</b> <b>Eggleston</b> exhibit at David Zwirner in Los Angeles,
which I had taken my son to just a few days before, was mentioned. And I ca=
n=E2=80=99t get enough of the artist <b>Anna</b> <b>Weyant</b>, who was not=
 only profiled in the issue but <i>also</i> painted Gerber for a second cov=
er. Oh, then there=E2=80=99s the chilling <b>Gregory</b> <b>Crewdson</b> ph=
otograph of Jacobs and his husband at their <b>Frank Lloyd Wright</b> home =
outside the city. <br/><br/>Marc=E2=80=99s <i>Vogue</i> was exactly what it=
 needed to be, and I hope it inspires more novel thinking at these establis=
hed titles. Unlike my mother-in-law, I don=E2=80=99t <i>really </i>collect =
magazines. But I=E2=80=99ll be saving this one.<br/></li></ul></td>
         </tr>
