the names brought up time and again include <b>Jonathan Anderson</b>,
<b>Maria Grazia Chiuri</b>, and, more recently, Saint Laurent=E2=80=99s <b>=
Anthony Vaccarello</b>=E2=80=94no change has materialized. Instead, it appe=
ars that Kering chairman and C.E.O. <b>Fran=C3=A7ois-Henri Pinault</b> and =
his deputy, <b>Francesca Bellettini</b>, have decided to focus on getting t=
he executive ranks in order. Bellettini moved one of her longtime deputies,=
 <b>Cedric</b> <b>Charbit</b>, into her old job running Saint Laurent, and =
gave <b>Gianfranco</b> <b>Gianangeli</b>=E2=80=94Saint Laurent=E2=80=99s ch=
ief commercial officer=E2=80=94Charbit=E2=80=99s old Balenciaga C.E.O. gig.=
 <br/><br/>Now, there are no vacancies. And while everyone didn=E2=80=99t e=
nd up where they thought they would (Gucci C.E.O. <b>Stefano</b> <b>Cantino=
</b> was originally rumored to be heading to Saint Laurent or into a group-=
level role, and Charbit to Gucci), Kering is more stable <i>now</i>=E2=80=
=94which is especially important as it navigates the market upheaval. I=E2=
=80=99m convinced that the company is determined to give De Sarno the three
years that he deserves to try to make it work, despite the tremendous furth=
er investment it will require. There is definitely traction at Gucci in the=
 U.S., though. Every week, I hear another anecdote about someone making a b=
ig purchase, or placing a custom order. Sabato has real fans now.<br/></td>
